\begin_layout Standard
For roughly two decades – between the early 1970s and the early 1990s –
 a Marxist variant of critical political economy was the dominant paradigm
 in economic geography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scott07economic"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This approach came under increasing criticism during the 1980s, and although
 they never refuted it on its own terms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "83"
key "sayer1liberalism"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, by the early 1990s critics had successfully mounted a two-pronged attack
 on it.
 They made a convincing case that actually existing capitalism is much more
 varied and flexible than what the traditional Marxist theory of the capitalist
 mode of production portrays and therefore that this theory is insufficient
 for some of the most important issues of the day.
 Instead, the field began to emphasize 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

middle-range theory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 focusing on capitalism's varied forms and processes.
 On a second front, critics identified axes of inequality and domination
 – such as gender or race – that Marxist political economy seemed unable
 to address with much success.
 This critique brought formerly peripheral axes of inequality and domination
 to the center of economic geography, supplanting formerly central concerns,
 most notably class.
 The net result was a shift in economic geography away from the received
 canons of the Marxist tradition, with its emphasis on big, geohistorical
 issues, and to theories aimed at a smaller scale, with more reliance on
 more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and varied investigations, and to a wider variety of research topics with
 virtually no cohesive framework to tie everything together.
 As a result, the field became fragmented, atomized, and isolated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "peck2012economic"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The very same fragmentation gave the field a tribal character, with each
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tribe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 turning inward, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfixed by its own theoretical eccentricities,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and away from each other, away from developments outside economic geography,
 and away from the big issues of the day 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "taylor2012textquoteleftisland"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Macroeconomic geographies,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 so prevalent during the heyday of the Marxist ascendancy, became a novelty
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hudson6risingpowers,peck2016macroeconomic"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Today the field remains mostly critical of and opposed to mainstream economics,
 and it frequently borrowed from the Marxist tradition, but in an ad hoc
 way.
 So 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "sheppard03geographical"
literal "true"

\end_inset

's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "320"
key "sheppard03geographical"
literal "true"

\end_inset

description of it as a heterodox form of geographical political economy
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

haunted by Marx: a post-Marxist subdiscipline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is apropos.
 Nonetheless, economic geography is tied together only by weak theoretical
 threads and lacks a cohesive, unifying theoretical framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As one might expect, the specific subject of land rent tracked this path
 very closely.
 Between the early 1970s and early 1990s it garnered considerable attention
 and was the topic of intense debate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "for a review"
before "see"
key "haila1990thetheory"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 But the seeds of division and discord were already visible 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kerr1996thetheory,haila1990thetheory"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and shortly thereafter economic geography's study of land rent underwent
 a period of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rupture
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and decline 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ward2016theshitty"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 What was left of it also became more isolated from the discipline of economics,
 even heterodox economics.
 This was no great shakes because heterodox economics itself had turned
 away from land rent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hudson2012incorporating"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "21"
key "ward2016theshitty"
literal "true"

\end_inset

attribute this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state of dilapidation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to three problem.
 First, scholars working on land rent failed to retain land rent as an economic
 category (ostensibly one with its own dynamics) apart from the inevitable
 contingent mediations present in any concrete situation.
 Second, because the Marxist tradition (at the time) made a strong distinction
 between value and price, geographical political economists never developed
 a mechanism for setting land prices similar to the bid-rent function in
 mainstream economics.
 Instead, researchers posited a class of landlords that functioned to set
 rent levels.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Instead of connecting their research to macro-level analyses and theories
 of the land-market, researcher have tended to adopt ...
 the rent categories as [a] political heuristic to expose extractive power
 relations within an institutional analysis ...
 or obfuscated the issue of rent altogether.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rent categories
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "ward2016theshitty"
literal "true"

\end_inset

are referring to are the ones Marx discusses in Volume 3 of 
\emph on
Capital:
\emph default
 differential, monopoly, and absolute rent.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 And third, confusion over absolute rent, failing to integrate it with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wider understandings of the dynamics of rent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "22"
key "ward2016theshitty"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

